[## [SECTION: Step 12 — The CI Pipeline Architecture]]


11
02:51:06,000 --> 02:51:12,000
Now let's build our GitHub Actions workflow.
We'll put it in .github/workflows/ci.yml

12
02:51:12,000 --> 02:51:18,000
The workflow runs on pushes to main and develop, and on pull requests.
It has seven jobs that run in parallel with dependencies.

13
02:51:18,000 --> 02:51:24,000
First, secret scanning with gitleaks.
It scans your git history for accidentally committed secrets.

14
02:51:24,000 --> 02:51:30,000
API keys, passwords, tokens that were committed by mistake.
gitleaks finds them even if they were deleted later.

15
02:51:30,000 --> 02:51:36,000
fetch-depth zero is critical. It fetches the full git history.
Otherwise, gitleaks only sees the latest commit.

16
02:51:36,000 --> 02:51:42,000
Second job. dependency vulnerability scan with pip-audit.
It checks if any of your Python packages have known CVEs.

17
02:51:42,000 --> 02:51:48,000
Third job. lint and type check.
ruff checks code style and common errors.

18
02:51:48,000 --> 02:51:54,000
mypy checks type annotations.
This catches bugs before runtime.

19
02:51:54,000 --> 02:52:00,000
Fourth job. unit tests.
These run fast with mocked dependencies.

20
02:52:00,000 --> 02:52:06,000
We set APP_ENV to testing, and provide test passwords.
We run pytest with coverage and fail if coverage drops below 50 percent.

21
02:52:06,000 --> 02:52:12,000
Fifth job. integration tests.
These require real PostgreSQL and Redis containers.

22
02:52:12,000 --> 02:52:18,000
GitHub Actions provides services for this.
We define a postgres container and a redis container.

23
02:52:18,000 --> 02:52:24,000
We apply the schema, then run pytest.
Integration tests only run on pushes, not on pull requests.

24
02:52:24,000 --> 02:52:30,000
Sixth job. build the Docker image.
This only runs on pushes to the main branch.

25
02:52:30,000 --> 02:52:36,000
We set up Docker Buildx for multi-platform builds.
We log in to GitHub Container Registry.

26
02:52:36,000 --> 02:52:42,000
We extract metadata for tags. branch name, commit SHA, and latest.
Then we build and push the image.

27
02:52:42,000 --> 02:52:48,000
Seventh job. container security scan with Trivy.
Trivy scans the image for CVEs in OS and Python packages.

28
02:52:48,000 --> 02:52:54,000
It produces a SARIF report. This gets uploaded to the GitHub Security tab.
You can see all vulnerabilities in your repository's security dashboard.

29
02:52:54,000 --> 02:53:00,000
Concurrency prevents multiple workflows from running simultaneously.
If a new push happens, the previous workflow is cancelled.

30
02:53:00,000 --> 02:53:06,000
This saves CI minutes and prevents wasted work.


[## [SECTION: Step 13 — Multi-Stage Dockerfile (Component #71)]]


31
02:53:06,000 --> 02:53:12,000
Now let's build our multi-stage Dockerfile.
We'll put it in infrastructure/docker/Dockerfile

32
02:53:12,000 --> 02:53:18,000
Let me explain three important Docker patterns.
First, layer caching order.

33
02:53:18,000 --> 02:53:24,000
Docker caches each layer. If nothing changed, it reuses the cache.
This makes builds much faster.

34
02:53:24,000 --> 02:53:30,000
Copy dependency files first. pyproject.toml changes rarely.
Install pip dependencies next. This layer is cached until pyproject.toml changes.

35
02:53:30,000 --> 02:53:36,000
Then copy application code. Code changes frequently.
But the pip install layer is still cached.

36
02:53:36,000 --> 02:53:42,000
Second pattern. non-root user.
Containers run as root by default.

37
02:53:42,000 --> 02:53:48,000
If an attacker escapes the container, they have root on the host.
Running as a non-root user limits the damage.

38
02:53:48,000 --> 02:53:54,000
We create a finrag user and group.
Then change ownership of the app directory and switch to that user.

39
02:53:54,000 --> 02:54:00,000
Third pattern. HEALTHCHECK in the image.
This checks if the container is still alive.

40
02:54:00,000 --> 02:54:06,000
The healthcheck runs curl to the health endpoint every 30 seconds.
It waits 40 seconds for startup before checking.

41
02:54:06,000 --> 02:54:12,000
This is redundant with Docker Compose and Kubernetes healthchecks.
But defense in depth means having it in the image as a fallback.

42
02:54:12,000 --> 02:54:18,000
The Dockerfile uses multi-stage builds.
First stage is builder. It installs dependencies and compiles anything needed.

43
02:54:18,000 --> 02:54:24,000
Second stage is production. It copies only the virtual environment and source code.
No build tools in the final image. This makes it smaller and more secure.

44
02:54:24,000 --> 02:54:30,000
We use a slim Python base image.
Alpine is even smaller but can have compatibility issues.

45
02:54:30,000 --> 02:54:36,000
Our Dockerfile is complete.
Now we can build secure, production-ready images.


[## [SECTION: Step 14 — Container Scanning with Trivy (Component #72)]]


46
02:54:36,000 --> 02:54:42,000
Now let's understand container scanning with Trivy.
Trivy scans the built image for CVEs in OS and Python packages.

47
02:54:42,000 --> 02:54:48,000
The workflow uploads results in SARIF format to GitHub Security tab.
This gives you a dashboard of all vulnerabilities.

48
02:54:48,000 --> 02:54:54,000
exit-code zero means Trivy reports findings but does not fail the build.
Change to one to block deployments with CRITICAL vulnerabilities.

49
02:54:54,000 --> 02:55:00,000
You can test Trivy locally before pushing.
Install Trivy, then run trivy image against your image.

50
02:55:00,000 --> 02:55:06,000
Scan with severity CRITICAL, HIGH and format table.
This shows you exactly what vulnerabilities exist.

51
02:55:06,000 --> 02:55:12,000
Our container scanning is integrated into CI.
Every image is scanned before deployment.


[## [SECTION: Step 15 — Secret Scanning with gitleaks (Component #73)]]


52
02:55:12,000 --> 02:55:18,000
Now let's understand secret scanning with gitleaks.
gitleaks scans your git history for secrets that were accidentally committed.

53
02:55:18,000 --> 02:55:24,000
The workflow uses the official gitleaks GitHub Action.
It scans the entire repository history.

54
02:55:24,000 --> 02:55:30,000
fetch-depth zero is critical. Without it, Actions only fetches the latest commit.
gitleaks needs full history to catch secrets that were added in commit A and deleted in commit B.

55
02:55:30,000 --> 02:55:36,000
Even if a secret is deleted, it still exists in the git object store.
Anyone who clones the repo can see it.

56
02:55:36,000 --> 02:55:42,000
You can test gitleaks locally before pushing.
gitleaks detect with the source flag.

57
02:55:42,000 --> 02:55:48,000
Add a dot gitleaks.toml file to allowlist false positives.
Test passwords in CI YAML, and placeholder values.

58
02:55:48,000 --> 02:55:54,000
Our secret scanning is integrated into CI.
If a secret is found, the workflow fails.


[## [SECTION: Step 16 — OPA Rego Policy (Component #74)]]


59
02:55:54,000 --> 02:56:00,000
Now let's look at the OPA Rego policy for Vault.
This validates Vault policy HCL files before they are applied.

60
02:56:00,000 --> 02:56:06,000
Three rules are enforced by the Rego policy.

61
02:56:06,000 --> 02:56:12,000
First, no wildcard write on secret paths.
This prevents secret star with write capability.

62
02:56:12,000 --> 02:56:18,000
Second, no delete on secret paths.
Application roles should never delete secrets.

63
02:56:18,000 --> 02:56:24,000
Third, no sudo capability except for admin policies.
And no sys slash access from non-admin workloads.

64
02:56:24,000 --> 02:56:30,000
Use the file from your repo as-is.
Test it with conftest.

65
02:56:30,000 --> 02:56:36,000
Install conftest. pip install conftest.
Create a test input with a bad policy that grants write on a wildcard path.

66
02:56:36,000 --> 02:56:42,000
Run conftest test against the input.
Using vault_policy.rego as the policy.

67
02:56:42,000 --> 02:56:48,000
Expected output shows failures.
The policy catches the wildcard write and the delete capability.

68
02:56:48,000 --> 02:56:54,000
Our OPA Rego policy is complete.
Vault policies are validated before they reach production.


[## [SECTION: Step 17 — Production Docker Compose]]


69
02:56:54,000 --> 02:57:00,000
Now let's set up the production Docker Compose configuration.
We'll put it in infrastructure/docker/docker-compose.prod.yml

70
02:57:00,000 --> 02:57:06,000
This runs the entire application stack in production.
We have five core services.

71
02:57:06,000 --> 02:57:12,000
The FastAPI application, PostgreSQL, Redis, Prometheus, and Grafana.

72
02:57:12,000 --> 02:57:18,000
First, the app service.
It builds the Docker image using the production target.

73
02:57:18,000 --> 02:57:24,000
Environment variables come from a dot env dot prod file.
All required variables have the colon question mark syntax.

74
02:57:24,000 --> 02:57:30,000
If POSTGRES_PASSWORD is missing, Docker Compose refuses to start.
This is fail-fast at startup.

75
02:57:30,000 --> 02:57:36,000
The app depends on postgres and redis with condition service_healthy.
It only starts after both dependencies are healthy.

76
02:57:36,000 --> 02:57:42,000
The app has its own healthcheck.
curl to the health endpoint every 30 seconds.

77
02:57:42,000 --> 02:57:48,000
This tells Docker if the container is alive.
If the healthcheck fails, the container can be restarted.

78
02:57:48,000 --> 02:57:54,000
Second, the PostgreSQL service.
We use the pgvector slash pg16 image.

79
02:57:54,000 --> 02:58:00,000
Environment variables include the database name, user, and password.
Notice the password is not using colon question mark here.

80
02:58:00,000 --> 02:58:06,000
It comes from the same environment variable.
But the check happens at the app level.

81
02:58:06,000 --> 02:58:12,000
Volumes mount persistent data storage.
And the init SQL scripts run on first start.

82
02:58:12,000 --> 02:58:18,000
Third, the Redis service.
Redis 7 on Alpine Linux for a small image size.

83
02:58:18,000 --> 02:58:24,000
The command configures the server.
Requirepass uses the password from environment.

84
02:58:24,000 --> 02:58:30,000
Maxmemory is set to 1 gigabyte.
The eviction policy is allkeys-lru, correct for a cache.

85
02:58:30,000 --> 02:58:36,000
Appendonly yes enables persistence to disk.
This means Redis survives container restarts.

86
02:58:36,000 --> 02:58:42,000
Fourth, Prometheus for metrics collection.
It scrapes the app's metrics endpoint every 10 seconds.

87
02:58:42,000 --> 02:58:48,000
Prometheus stores data for 30 days.
It has a web lifecycle enabled for reloads without restart.

88
02:58:48,000 --> 02:58:54,000
Fifth, Grafana for metrics visualization.
It connects to Prometheus as a data source.

89
02:58:54,000 --> 02:59:00,000
The admin password is set from environment variables.
User sign-up is disabled for security.

90
02:59:00,000 --> 02:59:06,000
We need to create the Prometheus configuration file.
It goes in infrastructure slash docker slash prometheus.

91
02:59:06,000 --> 02:59:12,000
Global scrape interval is 15 seconds.
Evaluation interval is also 15 seconds.

92
02:59:12,000 --> 02:59:18,000
Scrape configs define which targets to monitor.
One job for the financial-rag-api, target app port 8000.

93
02:59:18,000 --> 02:59:24,000
And one job for Prometheus itself, target localhost 9090.

94
02:59:24,000 --> 02:59:30,000
To start the production stack, first create a dot env dot prod file.
Copy from dot env example and edit with production values.

95
02:59:30,000 --> 02:59:36,000
Then run docker compose with the production compose file.
Use the dash dash env dash file flag to specify your environment file.

96
02:59:36,000 --> 02:59:42,000
Verify all services are running with docker compose ps.
You should see five services all in the Up state.

97
02:59:42,000 --> 02:59:48,000
Let me summarize the production architecture.

98
02:59:48,000 --> 02:59:54,000
The app service connects to PostgreSQL and Redis.
It exposes Prometheus metrics on the slash metrics endpoint.

99
02:59:54,000 --> 03:00:00,000
Prometheus scrapes those metrics every 10 seconds.
Grafana visualizes them in dashboards.

100
03:00:00,000 --> 03:00:06,000
All data is persisted in Docker volumes.
PostgreSQL data, Redis data, Prometheus data, and Grafana data.

101
03:00:06,000 --> 03:00:12,000
Our production Docker Compose stack is complete.
The entire application is ready for deployment.


[## [SECTION: Step 18 — Utility Scripts]]


102
03:00:12,000 --> 03:00:18,000
Now let's create the utility scripts for development.
These make starting and stopping the environment much easier.

103
03:00:18,000 --> 03:00:24,000
First, start.sh. This script starts the development environment.
It has error handling with set dash e uo pipefail.

104
03:00:24,000 --> 03:00:30,000
If any command fails, the script exits immediately.
This prevents running with half-initialized services.

105
03:00:30,000 --> 03:00:36,000
The script does preflight checks first.
It checks if dot env file exists.

106
03:00:36,000 --> 03:00:42,000
Then it sources the dot env file to load environment variables.
It sets all variables, then unsets the automatic export.

107
03:00:42,000 --> 03:00:48,000
It checks if docker is installed.
And if the docker daemon is actually running.

108
03:00:48,000 --> 03:00:54,000
Next, it starts the core services.
PostgreSQL and Redis with docker compose up minus d.

109
03:00:54,000 --> 03:01:00,000
The wait_healthy function loops until each container is healthy.
It checks docker inspect for the health status.

110
03:01:00,000 --> 03:01:06,000
It retries up to 30 times, waiting 2 seconds between tries.
If a container never becomes healthy, the script fails with an error.

111
03:01:06,000 --> 03:01:12,000
Then it asks if you want to start management tools.
pgAdmin and Redis Commander are in the tools profile.

112
03:01:12,000 --> 03:01:18,000
If you say yes, it runs docker compose with the profile flag.
These tools are optional and not required for the app to run.

113
03:01:18,000 --> 03:01:24,000
Finally, it prints a summary of where services are running.
PostgreSQL on localhost with the configured port.

114
03:01:24,000 --> 03:01:30,000
Redis on localhost with its port.
And if you started tools, pgAdmin on port 5050, Redis UI on port 8081.

115
03:01:30,000 --> 03:01:36,000
Second, stop.sh. This is the simplest script.
It just runs docker compose down.

116
03:01:36,000 --> 03:01:42,000
This stops all containers but preserves the data volumes.
Your PostgreSQL and Redis data remain on disk.

117
03:01:42,000 --> 03:01:48,000
Third, cleanup.sh. This is destructive.
It asks for confirmation before doing anything.

118
03:01:48,000 --> 03:01:54,000
If you type y or Y, it runs docker compose down with the minus v flag.
The minus v flag removes all named volumes.

119
03:01:54,000 --> 03:02:00,000
This deletes your PostgreSQL database, Redis data, and any other persistent storage.
Use this to completely reset your development environment.

120
03:02:00,000 --> 03:02:06,000
Make the scripts executable first.
chmod plus x scripts slash start.sh, stop.sh, and cleanup.sh.

121
03:02:06,000 --> 03:02:12,000
Here is the development workflow.
First, run dot slash scripts slash start.sh.

122
03:02:12,000 --> 03:02:18,000
This starts PostgreSQL and Redis.
It waits for them to be healthy.

123
03:02:18,000 --> 03:02:24,000
Do your development work.
Run your application, run tests.

124
03:02:24,000 --> 03:02:30,000
When you're done, run dot slash scripts slash stop.sh.
The data stays on disk for next time.

125
03:02:30,000 --> 03:02:36,000
If you want a completely fresh start, run dot slash scripts slash cleanup.sh.
This removes everything, including your data.

126
03:02:36,000 --> 03:02:42,000
Our utility scripts are complete.
Development environment management is now simple and consistent.


